comment.text: FF: Campid[onensis]: [Early ms. ownership inscription of Stift Kempten, a Benedictine abbey in Kempten, Bavaria, Germany. Founded in 752 under the patronage of the Virgin Mary and Saints Gordian and Epimachius, it was granted imperial immediacy by Henry IV in 1062; from the 12th century onward the abbot also carried the title of prince. comment.text:
Metal-cut printer's device of Guy Marchant of Paris:
"[T]he third of Guy Marchant's six devices ... At the top is a rebus consisting of musical notes, sol and la and the words Fides ficit, to represent the motto, 'Sola fides sufficit' (from the hymn, 'Pange lingua gloriosi,' of St. Thomas Aquinas). Below the motto are the initials, G and M, the G being set in type and the M cut in the block. Below these are two clasped hands issuing from clouds and flanked by angels. The device depicts the workshop of Saints Crispin and Crispinian, patron saints of shoemakers. It has been suggested that the presence of these saints might be explained if Marchant were a native of Soissons, where they were especially honored. Between the saints is a shield, with a book, possibly a Bible, held open by two hands. The word, sola (sole of the foot) and the boots in the shoeshop suggest the word marchant, a play on the printer's name."
--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 23. Established heading: Marchant, Guy

From his father, Henry Brevoort, he inherited about 6,000 volumes, mostly Americana, which were collected in Europe during the turbulent years from 1810 until 1832. To this library, Brevoort made large additions, until in 1875 it comprised about 10,000 volumes, many of them very rare and costly. He also collected medals and manuscripts. comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text:
Woodcut printer's device of Martin Landsberg of Leipzig:
Martin Landsberg, the first printer at Leipzig to use a device, imitated Peter Schöffer's design of two shields hanging from a branch ... There are various interpretations of the design on the shields. That on the left is described as a circle, crescent and star (BMC); a moon sign and star (Geldner); or a merchant's mark (a simplified bull's head and a star) (Moran). The right shield bears the arms of the printer's native city of Wurzburg; or, possibly it represents a town (Land) behind a mountain ('Berg'), constituting a play on the name, Landsberg.
--M. Harman, Printer's and publisher's devices in incunabula in the University of Illinois Library, no. 36. Cf. also E. Weil, Deutschen Druckerzeichen des XV. Jahrhunderts, no. 71c. Established heading: Landsberg, Martin, d. 1523

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Above: MDXIII Leonis X Pont. max. anno primo eidibus nouembr. Ex hispania fuit Romam aduectus puer natione Gallus annoru[m] xij Monstrum in pectore gerens ad forma[m] perfecti pueruli acephali brachijs tamen gracillimis sine manibus ostendentis caput suum intra pectus pueri condidisse et per paruum collum a pectore ip[s]ius dependere diuisis corporibus, ventribus inter se coherentibus genua pueri uix pedibus attingentis. Quodq[ue] mirum dictu est puer una cum monstro egerit, mingitq[ue], tamq[ue] cibo unius utriq[ue] alimenta prestentur. Et si quid monstrum tetigerit, puer statim sentit. H[a]ec non uulgaris fabula sed pleriq[ue] uiri fide digni cum Rom[a]e, tum in Hispania & Gallia hunc puerum mo[n]striferu[m] magnu[m] qu[a]estum facientem uiderunt. [Early ms. inscription recording the appearance in Rome in 1513 of a twelve-year-old French boy with a conjoined twin.]

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Beneath: 1 die veneris ija martij. 1515. Adolescens monstrifer nom[en] Jaquet Floquet postea peragratis pluribus Italie ciuitatibus questus causa genuam venit : ac hospitatus est in vicinia molis : et que de eo superius scripta sunt : hodie verissima fore deprehendi : duobus exceptis. nam monstrum ex stomaco : non ex pectore exit : nec egerit deficiente ano : mingit t[ame]n : et membrum virile habet. preterea non sunt plures dies : [que] monstrum h[abe]t tibias ita in poplitibus retractas : ut talis pedum suas nates attingat. cur ei ita acciderit : pleriq[ue] credunt : [qui]a monstrum adhuc crescens no[n] h[ab]ea[n]t solitum nutrime[n]tum : et ob hoc forte monstrifero breuiore[m] vita[m] portendit : ut et[iam] in aspectu de monstrat moestus et pallidus incedens : t[ame]n vultu modesto : et acco[m]modatis verbis : et quantum potui considerare circiter etatis anno[rum] xvj videtur. [Update in a different hand, dated 2 March 1515, on the anatomical peculiarities of the boy with the conjoined twin, here named Jaquet Floquet, whom the writer characterizes as gloomy and pale but also modest and well-spoken.]

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: First pass at a translation: 1513 In the first year of Pope Leo X, November 13 There was brought from Spain to Rome a twelve-year-old French boy bearing in his chest a monster in the form of a perfect little boy without a head but with very thin arms without hands, his head hidden within the boy's chest and hanging down by a small neck from the chest of the same, with separate bodies, their bellies cleaving together but the feet scarcely touching the boy's knees. And, strange to say, the boy eliminates together with the monster and urinates, and food provides each of them with nourishment. And if something touched the monster, the boy immediately felt it. This is no popular tale; many trustworthy men in Rome as well as Spain and France saw this monster-bearing boy making a great profit. On the first Friday, 2 March 1515. The monster-bearing youth named Jaquet Floquet, after having traveled to many Italian cities for profit, came to Geneva and stayed in the vicinity of the wharf, and those things which were written above about him I have found today to be quite true, with two exceptions. The monster actually issues from the [boy's] stomach, not the chest; nor does it eliminate, lacking an anus, but it nevertheless urinates and has a male member. In addition there are not many days [but that?] the monster has its knees bent to its hocks so that its feet touch its own buttocks. [As to] why it has befallen him thus, many believe that the still-growing monster does not have its accustomed nourishment, and perhaps because of this portends a shorter life for the monster-bearing [youth], so that in form he also appears gloomy and pale [...], but nevertheless of modest bearing and well-spoken, and as far as I could judge he seems to be about 16 years old.

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Above: Venetijs repertum in arca latente : in qua vas futile clausum erat. Plutoni sacrum munus ne attingite fures. Ignotum est vobis hoc : quod in orbe latet. Nam[que] elementa graui clausit digesta labore Vase sub hoc modico maximus olybius. Adsit secundo custos sibi copia cornu : Ne pretium tanti depereat laticis. In eodem aliud uas fictile fuit inculsum cum his versibus. Abite hinc pessimi fures : Vos qui uoltis cum v[est]ris oculis emissitijs. Abite hinc cum v[est]ro mercurio petasato : caduceato[que] Maximus maximum donum plutoni hu[n]c sacrum facit. Metaratij viri consumatissimi ep[isto]la de re ista ad amicum. Nihil ex {corr. from: est} om[n]i anti[qui]tate uidisti mirabilius mi alphene: in uase illo interiori lucerna fuit fictilis mire pulcritudinis lumine tot seculis mextinato : Su[per] eam due ampulle parue : aurum in altera : in altera argentum fuit : vtrun[que] li[qui]dum. et ut ex ramentis cognoscitur : primarium Argentum : Aurum uero obryzum. Ego chimie artis : si modo uera potest esse ars chimia iurare possum elementa fuisse et materiam. Omnia : vas utru[m][que] cum epigra[m]matib[us] : lucerna : ampulle : aurum : olim in munere ad me uenere : et penes me sunt : que si videas : obstupeseas : et ego cum mille aureis no[n] sum co[m]mutaturus : vale. Da versus amicis rescribendos : et camerti pontifici : at[que] amico Gratiano in primis uetustatis studiossimis. [Ms. transcription of two Latin verses associated with Olybius's lamp, part of a classical burial putatively discovered still burning around the turn of the 16th century, followed by the text of a letter purportedly written by the Italian humanist Francesco Maturanzio (d. 1518) to a friend regarding this discovery. Cf. Corpus Inscriptionarum Latinarum V, pt. I, p. 22*, no. 194* (transcribed here).]

Biblioteca Nazionale Centrale di Firenze, v. 1, fasc. 1 (Rome: Presso i Principali Librai, 1885), p. 457) in left-hand column with emended text in right-hand head column. comment.text: Harold Cramer's description at his excellent cartobibliography of Pennsylvania maps www.mapsofpa.com/antiquemaps19.htm "1698.1 PENNSYLVANIA AND WEST JERSEY. This map by Philip Lea, London, is from An Historical and Geographical Account of the Province and Country of Pennsylvania and of West-New-Jersey in America by Gabriel Thomas, published by A. Baldwin, London 1698. The book was reprinted in 1848 by H. A. Brady, New York (see page 671 of Phillips), and in 1935 by A. M. Aurand Jr., which is the image shown here. This map also appeared in Lea's atlas Hydrographia Universalis or The Sea Coasts of the Known Parts of the World, London 1700; and in a German edition of Thomas, Continuatio der beschreibung der landschafft Pensylvaniae, Frankfurt and Leipzig 1702; see Docktor #200L2, #202B5. Burden #728 dates this map circa 1696 from its appearance in the Hydrographia Universalis. There were several 17th century accounts of Pennsylvania written; Penn himself wrote at least 8 versions of his Some Account of the Province of Pennsylvania... . In 1685 appeared Good Order Established in Pennsilvania & New-Jersey in America, by Thomas Budd and printed by Philadelphia's first printer, William Bradford. In 1692 Bradford also printed A Short Description of Pennsylvania by Richard Frame. Around 1700 Francis Daniel Pastorius published Umständige Geographische Beschreibung der zu allerletzt erfundenen Provintz Pensylvaniae ... (A Particular Geographical Description of the lately discovered Province of Pennsylvania); indicative of the early German settlement. "

comment.author: 95166551@N04
comment.text: Great map. No surprise the longitude lines are missing in 1698, as we had no idea how to measure it well, and the location of the prime meridian was in dispute. I'm a bit surprised though in how far off the latitude is though. Philly is south of 40N, and the original lease of Delaware territory to the Penn family excluded any land north of 40N within 12 miles of New Castle, despite New Castle being 25 miles south of 40N. Ultimately, the result of this error was beneficial to PA as the final north south border of MD/PA at 39N 43' surveyed by Mason and Dixon was much closer to the 40N mark on this this map.

The lion's head is the emblem or arms of Jo. Chardalli Cantor Metensis (BMC IV 12-13 on the 1471 Bible of Sweynheym and Pannartz, IC.17163). A 'grand chantre' presided over the choral work of a church, in this case the cathedral of Metz. But how is the paper on which they here appear attached to the leaf? It seems to be a pasted or laid-in slip -- is it provably original to this book?

Martin Davies

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: BMC does not explicitly associate the coat of arms with Chardallus's ownership inscription -- does it mean to? Bod-Inc's index of provenances ascribes to Chardallus a different coat of arms: "azure, a leopard’s face, with five thistles issuing from the mouth, all proper." A large portion of the tail margin of the leaf has been excised and replaced with the piece of paper containing this illustration. I suspect that the excision removed a previous mark of ownership, but have no proof of that or of the time when the replacement was made.

comment.author: 90835370@N04
comment.text: The statement in Bod-Inc that Chardallus had arms "azure, a leopard’s face, with five thistles issuing from the mouth, all proper" is referred to the Bible in the BL, which does not have those arms, but precisely the arms found in the Penn book (including the rays around the head). The books that do have them (more exactly a lion's head with three thistles - no rays), namely BL, C.13.e.2 S&P Jerome 1468 vol. 2; Hague, MMW 4 A 12, S&P Aquinas 1470; and MMW 2 D 6, Lauer Aquinas c. 1470 (both pictured in  Vroege boekdrukkunst uit Italie 1987), and a Lauer Chrysostom shown in  Hoepli, Manoscritti, incunabuli e libri figurati del secolo XVI. Vendita all’asta  MCMXXX, no. 75 and Tav. LXVII, and presumably the Bod-Inc Castellione, have no inscription of Chardalli's ownership. On the other hand, his name *is* found in e.g. MS Metz 211 (now destroyed, but microfilmed) where the Catalogue général des manuscripts des bibliothèques publiques des départements, tome V, Paris 1879, p. 94 says: « De la cathédrale de Metz. Signé : « Jo. Chardalli. » - Sur le premier feuillet, un emblème, dans lequel se voit un écu d’azur portant en coeur une tête bronzée de lion, posée de face. »

comment.author: 90835370@N04
comment.text:
Also, as I learn today, BnF Rés. J. 1830 has the wreathed and rayed lion’s head (unthistled) on first text page of Lauer’s 1471 Eutropius, and “Jo. Chardalli Cantor” under the colophon .
